03836nam a22005655i 9780889206687DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19861986xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892066877 a10.51644/97808892066872doi  a(DE-B1597)667422  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBR100.N5bN49 1986eb 7aREL0510002bisacsh04a233  aBN 29892rvk0(DE-625)rvk/13741:1 aNewman, Jay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Mental Philosophy of John Henry Newman /cJay Newman. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[1986] 4c©1986  a1 online resource (221 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNewman's Philosophical Project -- tModes of Apprehension and Belief -- tReligious Belief as "Real" -- tDegrees of Belief -- tFormal and Informal Inference -- tThe Illative Sense -- tMens ad Cor Loquitur -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJohn Henry Newman's writings in theology, apologetics, history, poetry, and educational theory, among other fields, made him one of the most controversial as well as influential modern Christian thinkers. Central to his religious vision was his innovative and complex "mental philosophy," first sketched out at Oxford during his Anglican years and developed in its most detailed form in his celebrated Grammar of Assent. In The Mental Philosophy of John Henry Newman, Jay Newman (no relation) presents a careful scrutiny of John Henry Newman's phenomenology of belief and epistemology in the context of the nineteenth-century cleric's major work. He departs from traditional historical and technological approaches to Newman's work on belief and critically examines Newman's contribution in this area from the standpoint of contemporary analytical philosophy. The study examines the sources, aims, and implications of Newman's philosophical project. While it draws attention to the positive value of Newman's original approach, it also explores the weaknesses and dangers of Newman's main phenomenological and epistemological theories. Jay Newman not only makes a significant original contribution to the field of Newman studies but also provides us with a guide to some of the problems and confusions of the Grammar of Assent.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFaith. 0aNewman, John Henry, 1801-1890. Essay in aid of a grammar of assent. 0aReligion. 0aTheism. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920668740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889206687423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889206687/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles